43:06.620 --> 43:09.180
Anytime you need a bus held,
I am your guy.

43:09.420 --> 43:12.173
-Erin's teeth are looking good.
-Thanks to you.

43:12.420 --> 43:14.729
I hope she remembers to wear
her retainer.

43:15.140 --> 43:16.732
You know how kids are at camp.

43:16.980 --> 43:20.495
The minute my Kevin gets off that bus,
it's "Goodbye, biteplate."

43:20.940 --> 43:22.339
Is that for you?

43:23.940 --> 43:27.250
When Deirdre and I divorced,
I decided to learn how to cook.

43:27.540 --> 43:29.531
The Wok-y World of Thai Cooking?

43:29.780 --> 43:30.974
I'm branching out.

43:31.180 --> 43:33.978
I'm taking a Thai cooking course
this summer.

43:34.260 --> 43:37.332
Really? I've always been interested
in Asian cooking.

43:37.580 --> 43:38.649
Really?

43:39.100 --> 43:40.374
Why don't you join me?

43:42.980 --> 43:44.652
When I think about it...

43:44.980 --> 43:47.414
. . .over the years there were
less and less moments. . .

43:47.660 --> 43:49.093
. . .in the course of the day. . .

43:49.340 --> 43:52.059
. . .when Ben and I actually made
real eye contact.

43:52.300 --> 43:54.655
You are not gonna believe
what happened.

43:54.940 --> 43:57.295
-What?
-He's almost asleep.

43:58.700 --> 44:00.656
Maybe it was the stuff of life.

44:01.060 --> 44:02.778
Who 's taking Erin to school?

44:03.380 --> 44:06.213
Who will pick up Josh
from his clarinet lessons?

44:06.900 --> 44:09.209
After a while, there was
a disturbing comfort...

44:09.460 --> 44:11.416
...in not having to deal
with each other...

44:11.660 --> 44:15.175
...because somehow you just
get used to the disconnection.

44:16.140 --> 44:19.974
Even at night, when we could finally
come together, we faced forward.

44:20.180 --> 44:23.092
Yeah, we were tired,
but I think we were afraid...

44:23.340 --> 44:26.491
... that if we faced each other,
there'd be nothing there.

44:26.940 --> 44:28.817
We're learning Mee Krob next week.

44:29.260 --> 44:30.488
Mee Krob.

44:31.820 --> 44:33.412
I'll let you know.

44:37.180 --> 44:39.740
I'll call you. Oh, you call me.

44:44.860 --> 44:47.420
When we drove to the camp
for Parents ' Weekend...

44:47.620 --> 44:49.576
...I was scared to face the kids.

44:50.220 --> 44:54.372
You'd talk about it with a best friend.
But Katie had been my best friend.

44:54.580 --> 44:58.573
Now I didn 't know what we were,
except Josh and Erin 's parents.

45:24.340 --> 45:25.375
What?

45:27.140 --> 45:28.414
Nothing.

45:31.220 --> 45:32.733
--is nothing?

45:34.140 --> 45:36.256
This is not going to be easy.

45:37.700 --> 45:40.612
The kids do not need to be burdened
with our problems.

45:40.860 --> 45:42.498
They have half a summer left.

45:42.740 --> 45:45.413
Like my plan was to burden
the kids with our problems.

45:45.660 --> 45:48.777
Jesus Christ, will you give me
some fucking credit?

45:55.300 --> 45:56.574
I missed you.

45:56.980 --> 45:58.618
I missed you so much.

45:58.860 --> 46:00.418
I missed you both so much.

46:03.580 --> 46:05.252
Dad, pull yourself together.

46:05.620 --> 46:07.611
Dad, get off of me!

46:09.300 --> 46:12.133
You guys both look terrific.
Show us your bunks.

46:12.980 --> 46:14.618
I wanna see your bunks too.

46:14.860 --> 46:17.420
Did you get your favorite room?
The Acorn Cabin?

46:17.660 --> 46:18.979
Yeah, we did.

46:19.220 --> 46:21.256
We got the Acorn Cabin.

47:06.540 --> 47:08.019
God, I hate lying to them.

47:08.260 --> 47:10.854
Me too. We're not even good at it.

47:11.100 --> 47:13.614
Even if we were good at it,
they'd still know.

47:36.380 --> 47:37.574
What is that?

47:38.100 --> 47:38.976
What's what?

47:39.220 --> 47:42.257
-The thing you just put in your mouth.
-It's my biteplate.

47:42.460 --> 47:45.418
-Biteplate?
-Yeah. It's my biteplate.

47:45.660 --> 47:48.299
-Why do you have a biteplate?
-For my bite.

47:49.340 --> 47:50.659
What's wrong with your bite?

47:51.780 --> 47:53.338
It's askew.

47:53.580 --> 47:54.376
Askew?

47:54.580 --> 47:56.172
Yes, it's askew.

47:56.740 --> 47:59.812
So this would be an attempt
to de-skew it?

48:05.100 --> 48:06.818
You order room service?

48:14.180 --> 48:16.250
-What's the matter?
-Nothing. I'm okay.

48:16.500 --> 48:17.774
Honey, are you okay?

48:18.020 --> 48:19.817
I'm okay. I'm fine.

48:20.060 --> 48:23.052
I couldn't sleep, so
I snuck out after lights out.

48:23.540 --> 48:25.815
I just wanted to sleep
with you guys.

48:28.100 --> 48:31.809
It's okay. I'll call the camp
and let them know you're here.

48:36.620 --> 48:38.815
Why is the bed made up on the couch?

48:40.780 --> 48:44.375
Daddy was doing a little reading,
and I didn't wanna wake Mommy up.

49:15.900 --> 49:18.778
Sometimes you just can 't
climb out of the abyss.

49:19.380 --> 49:21.610
I thought of last summer,
when we still hoped...

49:21.860 --> 49:24.613
... that if we put ourselves
in some idyllic setting...

49:24.820 --> 49:27.209
... we'd somehow get rid
of all the tension...

49:27.460 --> 49:28.973
...jump-start our marriage...

49:29.220 --> 49:32.132
...and rediscover why we fell in love
in the first place.

49:32.340 --> 49:34.410
So last year,
after Parents ' Weekend...

49:34.660 --> 49:37.220
... we thought maybe
in a trattoria in Venice...

49:37.460 --> 49:40.816
...looking at a beautiful sunset,
next to a bottle of Chianti...

49:41.020 --> 49:43.659
... we just might find a set
ofjumper cables.

49:45.460 --> 49:48.054
How you doing?
Two Italian ices, please.

49:48.300 --> 49:52.179
Honey, you don't have to say Italian.
We're here. They know.

49:52.540 --> 49:56.215
So if I'm in Belgium, and I order
a Belgian waffle, I just say waffle?

49:56.460 --> 49:59.452
Like if you were in Ireland
and you wanted Irish stew. . .

49:59.700 --> 50:01.133
. . .you'd just say stew.

50:01.380 --> 50:03.769
If you're in China and
you want Chinese food. . .

50:04.020 --> 50:05.692
. . .you say, "Bring on the food."

50:06.780 --> 50:09.772
We couldn't help but overhear
your delightful repartee.

50:10.020 --> 50:12.375
We're the Kirbys from Cleveland.
And you are. . .?

50:12.620 --> 50:14.815
-The Mansons.
-From Spawn Ranch.

50:18.900 --> 50:19.889
That's a good one.

50:35.220 --> 50:37.176
Look, right there.
The red cape.

50:37.420 --> 50:38.614
I like that.

50:44.220 --> 50:45.096
It's you. . .

50:45.340 --> 50:46.170
. . .people.

50:46.420 --> 50:49.378
-The Kirbys from Cleveland.
-Joanie and Eddie.

50:49.620 --> 50:52.737
How could we forget?
We haven't stopped talking about you.

50:53.180 --> 50:56.058
This is fate. We have to
get together, break bread.

50:56.300 --> 50:58.939
Sounds great.
We're at the Hotel Pasta e Fagioli.

51:00.060 --> 51:02.290
You call us.
We're at the Europa Regina.

51:02.540 --> 51:04.690
Great. We'll call you.

51:04.940 --> 51:06.009
Oh, right on!

51:08.540 --> 51:09.416
Look at this.

51:09.660 --> 51:11.378
-This is beautiful.
-This way.

51:11.660 --> 51:13.696
-Thank you.
-Canal-side seating.

51:13.940 --> 51:15.168
Very nice.

51:17.660 --> 51:19.537
Oh, my God!

51:20.500 --> 51:21.899
Meant to be!

51:22.820 --> 51:24.731
Kismet! Kismet!

51:25.140 --> 51:28.849
We went looking for your hotel,
but we couldn't find it anywhere.

51:29.100 --> 51:32.775
-Yeah, it's pretty hard to find.
-Well, all's well that ends well.

51:34.980 --> 51:38.211
It was just like fate,
the first time I met Joanie.

51:38.460 --> 51:41.850
I worked on the 6th floor,
and Eddie worked on the 4th floor.

51:42.100 --> 51:44.295
-Hand to God.
-Every day in the cafeteria. . .

51:44.500 --> 51:46.934
-. . .on the third floor--
-I saw Joanie at the salad bar.

51:47.180 --> 51:49.410
And she smiled at me.
Not just a smile.

51:49.660 --> 51:51.457
I mean, a really big smile.

51:52.260 --> 51:54.820
One day at the salad bar
at Beefsteak Charlie's. . .

51:55.060 --> 51:57.255
. . .I thought I saw her
at that salad bar.

51:57.500 --> 51:59.889
-But it wasn't me.
-It wasn't Joanie!

52:00.740 --> 52:04.574
What are the odds of another person
at a salad bar looking like Joanie. . .

52:04.820 --> 52:06.492
. . .and yet not being Joanie?

52:07.300 --> 52:09.495
What, like a trillion to one?

52:09.740 --> 52:11.412
Could be higher than that.

52:11.660 --> 52:15.539
Anyway, when I realized it wasn't
Joanie, I was so disappointed.

52:15.780 --> 52:19.568
And I began to think about how much
I'd hoped that it was Joanie.

52:19.820 --> 52:22.129
But at this point
you still hadn't met.

52:22.380 --> 52:26.896
No. And I couldn't get over how much
I wanted this person to be Joanie.

52:27.140 --> 52:29.813
And I think that was
the defining moment.

52:30.060 --> 52:33.211
I went back to my wife at the table
at Beefsteak Charlie's. . .

52:33.460 --> 52:37.169
. . .and I realized I felt more alive
thinking about that stranger. . .

52:37.420 --> 52:41.208
. . .I thought was Joanie than I did
with the stranger who was my wife.

52:41.460 --> 52:43.576
We were both in marriages
we'd outgrown.

52:43.820 --> 52:46.573
You know, maybe I didn't
wanna admit it, but maybe. . .

52:46.780 --> 52:50.295
. . .I didn't like myself enough
to be with someone who liked me.

52:50.540 --> 52:53.259
Can you imagine anybody
not liking Eddie Kirby?

52:53.540 --> 52:55.417
I'm not so perfect.

52:55.660 --> 52:57.218
Beg to differ!

52:57.460 --> 53:02.295
That year we both mustered up
enough courage to leave our marriages.

53:02.540 --> 53:04.258
So at this point you had met.

53:05.340 --> 53:06.170
Still hadn't met.

53:07.020 --> 53:10.808
But, you know, after you've had
such a horrible marriage. . .

53:11.060 --> 53:13.813
. . .you don't wanna make
the same mistakes twice.

53:14.060 --> 53:16.369
So I made an inner pact with myself.

53:16.580 --> 53:19.970
I said, "Eddie, you will never
let anger build up to the point. . .

53:20.180 --> 53:22.011
. . .where you don't like
your partner."

53:22.260 --> 53:24.535
-I made the same pact.
-That became our credo.

53:24.780 --> 53:27.248
"Never go to bed angry."

53:27.780 --> 53:29.975
So now we talk everything through.

53:30.220 --> 53:33.656
We won't let even the tiniest pea
be under our mattress.

53:33.900 --> 53:36.130
That's why we never eat in bed.

53:39.780 --> 53:41.452
Me too.

53:44.620 --> 53:46.338
Who 'd have thought the Kirbys...

53:46.540 --> 53:48.815
... the happiest couple
never to have met...

53:49.060 --> 53:51.858
... would be the greatest
aphrodisiac known to man?

54:16.260 --> 54:19.013
If only you could bottle
that unfettered state of mind...

54:19.260 --> 54:21.216
... that comes with being
on foreign soil...

54:21.700 --> 54:23.099
... to just hold on to it...

54:23.340 --> 54:25.774
...even for a day, an evening...

54:26.500 --> 54:27.774
...an hour.

54:28.220 --> 54:31.098
Last year, when we
got back from Italy, God knows...

54:31.300 --> 54:33.097
... we gave it a try.

54:47.420 --> 54:48.773
Hey, look at this.

54:49.340 --> 54:53.379
While we were away, we got a message
from His Holiness, the Dalai Lama.

54:55.020 --> 54:57.090
About a softball team
he's getting started.

54:58.700 --> 55:02.375
You wanna write a letter to the kids
together, let them know we're back?

55:07.580 --> 55:10.253
"Dear Josh. . .

55:10.940 --> 55:12.293
. . .and Erin."

55:12.740 --> 55:15.459
Oh, sure. You get the easy part.

55:18.940 --> 55:19.850
"We're. . .

55:21.180 --> 55:22.329
. . .back."

55:25.540 --> 55:27.132
"From. . .

55:27.980 --> 55:29.049
. . .Europe."

55:30.020 --> 55:32.409
That's not a sentence.
It's a preposition and a continent.

55:32.660 --> 55:34.890
I crossed out your period
and made a sentence.

55:35.140 --> 55:38.052
See? "We're back from Europe."
Your turn.

55:38.300 --> 55:39.210
Thank you.

55:40.100 --> 55:43.854
Exclamation point.
Comma. Close parentheses.

55:44.100 --> 55:46.011
"But I. . .

55:46.660 --> 55:48.571
. . .don't want to talk. . .

55:48.820 --> 55:51.050
. . .about grammar."

55:51.300 --> 55:55.532
Colon. "I want to. . .

55:56.260 --> 55:58.251
. . .make love to. . .

55:58.500 --> 56:00.570
. . .your mother."

56:02.100 --> 56:04.011
No, you didn't write that.

56:06.900 --> 56:09.460
What? I do. I want to.

56:09.700 --> 56:11.418
After we finish the letter.

56:11.620 --> 56:15.533
No, let's make love right now.
Then we write the letter.

56:15.780 --> 56:18.931
Come on, we only had
a couple of sentences to go.

56:19.180 --> 56:22.172
In Europe, you would've
made love first.

56:23.140 --> 56:25.654
-What's that supposed to mean?
-Nothing.

56:25.900 --> 56:28.414
-That I'm not spontaneous?
-I'm not saying that.

56:28.660 --> 56:30.298
But that's what you implied.

56:30.540 --> 56:32.690
That in Europe I'd have
made love, but here--

56:32.940 --> 56:34.976
I don't want us to get to the point. . .

56:35.220 --> 56:38.451
. . .where we can't make love unless
there's a concierge downstairs.

56:38.700 --> 56:43.012
I wanted to take three minutes
to finish a letter to our children. . .

56:43.260 --> 56:44.534
. . .who I haven't seen--

56:44.780 --> 56:48.216
What's that supposed to mean?
That I don't care about our children?

56:48.460 --> 56:50.576
If I finish the letter,
I could be spontaneous.

56:50.780 --> 56:53.578
That's not spontaneous!
That's making an appointment!

56:53.780 --> 56:56.340
I was in the mood
for unscheduled affection. . .

56:56.540 --> 56:58.496
. . .but sorry, we're home. I forgot. . .

56:58.740 --> 57:01.049
. . .everything's gotta be
on a schedule!

57:01.900 --> 57:05.017
You try raising children
where everything's unscheduled. . .

57:05.260 --> 57:07.012
. . .when everything's spontaneous!

57:07.260 --> 57:10.457
You know what? The kids need
a little spontaneity too!

57:10.940 --> 57:12.578
I know that!

57:12.820 --> 57:16.972
I'm sick and tired of being
the designated driver of this marriage!

57:17.220 --> 57:19.939
Nobody designated you!
It's a role you gave yourself!

57:20.180 --> 57:22.216
Bullshit! You gave me that role!

57:22.460 --> 57:26.453
Because God forbid Ben should ever
remember to cancel the newspapers. . .

57:26.700 --> 57:28.292
. . .or put washer fluid in his car. . .

57:28.540 --> 57:31.213
. . .or participate in disciplining
his children. . .

57:31.460 --> 57:34.452
. . .instead of flirting on the phone
with your girlfriend!

57:34.700 --> 57:36.372
You're not bringing that up again!

57:36.580 --> 57:38.775
You're damn straight
I'll bring it up again!

57:39.020 --> 57:40.772
I haven't spoken to her
in six months!

57:41.020 --> 57:43.409
Not once have you seen it
through my eyes!

57:43.660 --> 57:46.732
We don't have a pea under our mattress.
You know what we have?

57:46.980 --> 57:48.049
A fucking watermelon!

57:48.300 --> 57:50.370
And you never wanna deal with it!

57:50.620 --> 57:52.258
Oh, fuck it!

57:52.700 --> 57:54.213
Jesus!

58:01.660 --> 58:03.173
Welcome home.

58:11.020 --> 58:12.294
Bye, Dad.

58:12.780 --> 58:14.532
-Thanks.
-I love you.

58:15.620 --> 58:17.258
-Bye, Mom.
-Buddy.

58:19.380 --> 58:20.608
Love you.

58:21.580 --> 58:23.298
See you guys in a month.

58:29.700 --> 58:31.053
Bye, you guys.

58:31.980 --> 58:33.379
-Bye, Daddy.
-Couple of weeks.

58:33.580 --> 58:35.491
-Watch your toes.
-See you.

58:35.740 --> 58:37.093
Bye, kids.

58:52.340 --> 58:54.649
Do you think we should get
one lawyer or two?

58:59.100 --> 59:00.135
One.

59:01.700 --> 59:04.419
Maybe we can at least
make this part. . . .

59:06.980 --> 59:11.098
All I care about is that we make it
as easy for the kids as possible.

59:15.420 --> 59:19.652
I'm sure you noticed the bathroom has
the original tiling from the '20s.

59:19.940 --> 59:20.770
It's nice.

59:20.980 --> 59:24.177
You know, since you're a writer,
I know you'd appreciate. . .

59:24.420 --> 59:26.809
. . .that the sister
of Bette Davis' chauffeur. . .

59:27.060 --> 59:30.177
. . .once had Thanksgiving
in the apartment next door.

59:30.780 --> 59:31.895
Really?

59:32.900 --> 59:35.130
Are there any other kids
in this building?

59:35.380 --> 59:39.168
Oodles! Including, if I might add,
the nephew of the actor. . .

59:39.380 --> 59:42.611
. . .who jumped third into
the fourth lifeboat on Titanic.

59:42.820 --> 59:45.414
Rent the film, you'll see.
I'll introduce you.

59:45.660 --> 59:49.448
I'm showing it to another family today,
but if you're interested. . .

59:49.700 --> 59:52.578
. . .I can hold it for you,
give your wife a look-see--

59:52.780 --> 59:53.610
I'm interested.

59:53.860 --> 59:57.773
Who wouldn't be? Look how the light
from that window fills the room.

59:58.380 --> 01:00:00.052
When I showed this apartment. . .

01:00:00.260 --> 01:00:02.979
. . .to the man who did the voice
of Charlie the Tuna. . .

01:00:03.220 --> 01:00:06.769
. . .he said, and I quote,
"Wow," unquote.

01:00:07.020 --> 01:00:08.772
I think that says it all.

01:00:11.300 --> 01:00:12.972
First, you put olive oil. . .

01:00:13.220 --> 01:00:14.858
. . .garlic and tofu.

01:00:15.100 --> 01:00:17.534
SautÃ© until garlic turn light brown.

01:00:17.860 --> 01:00:21.091
Make sure that your wok have
a strong heat underneath it.

01:00:21.340 --> 01:00:24.218
Now take an egg and crack it
to the hot oil.

01:00:26.260 --> 01:00:30.048
Make sure all the ingredients
are cooked thoroughly.

01:00:31.380 --> 01:00:32.290
You okay?

01:00:32.540 --> 01:00:34.576
Yeah, I'm fine.

01:00:35.420 --> 01:00:37.570
Now we add some Pad Thai noodle.

01:00:39.380 --> 01:00:42.929
I saw Deirdre up at Parents' Weekend,
but I didn't see you.

01:00:43.180 --> 01:00:44.977
I went up the weekend before.

01:00:45.220 --> 01:00:47.051
You know, since the divorce. . .

01:00:47.300 --> 01:00:50.815
. . .it's a lot easier for everyone
if we come up at separate times.

01:00:51.220 --> 01:00:54.053
Kevin and I took a great hike
up to that waterfall.

01:00:54.300 --> 01:00:55.858
You and Ben take that hike?

01:00:56.100 --> 01:00:58.250
Yeah, it was beautiful.

01:00:58.940 --> 01:01:01.408
Spice it up with some chili pepper.

01:01:01.660 --> 01:01:04.572
You know, spicy food
make a better lover.

01:01:04.820 --> 01:01:06.970
The hotter you eat,
the hotter you get.

01:01:08.380 --> 01:01:10.655
Well, the spicier the better for me.

01:01:12.220 --> 01:01:13.335
Rice vinegar.

01:01:17.340 --> 01:01:18.693
Does Ben like Thai food?

01:01:21.220 --> 01:01:22.778
You and Ben been to Tommy Tang's?

01:01:22.980 --> 01:01:24.299
Ben and I are di--

01:01:24.980 --> 01:01:26.095
Separated.

01:01:27.540 --> 01:01:29.053
Gee, I had no idea.

01:01:29.300 --> 01:01:31.495
We're not really telling people.

01:01:31.740 --> 01:01:33.412
I understand.

01:01:33.940 --> 01:01:36.135
I'm so sorry. How long?

01:01:37.100 --> 01:01:40.934
72 hours, four weeks, five years. . .

01:01:41.180 --> 01:01:43.375
. . .depending on when
you start counting.

01:01:43.620 --> 01:01:46.612
I'm really sorry.
I know how hard it can be.

01:01:49.620 --> 01:01:51.133
This will sound crazy. . .

01:01:51.380 --> 01:01:54.611
. . .but I always enjoyed
Erin and Josh's appointments. . .

01:01:54.860 --> 01:01:57.613
. . .because it gave me a chance
to get to know you.

01:01:58.180 --> 01:02:00.853
But when you called me
about your bite. . .

01:02:01.140 --> 01:02:05.418
. . .I felt myself looking forward to it
because I knew we'd be alone.

01:02:06.660 --> 01:02:09.538
And just tell me if it's too soon. . .

01:02:10.380 --> 01:02:13.611
. . .but I wondered if maybe you
wanted to have dinner sometime?

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:17.298
We are having dinner.

01:02:19.100 --> 01:02:22.410
I was thinking of something
that didn't involve a teacher.

01:02:25.980 --> 01:02:27.811
You always hear people say...

01:02:28.020 --> 01:02:30.215
... they stayed too long
in a bad marriage.

01:02:30.460 --> 01:02:34.055
For the longest time, I never thought
of my marriage as being bad.

01:02:34.300 --> 01:02:37.815
I thought love was something you
were allowed to fall in and out of.

01:02:38.020 --> 01:02:39.897
You know, peaks and valleys.

01:02:40.420 --> 01:02:42.012
But after a while...

01:02:42.260 --> 01:02:45.297
... the peaks get lower
and further apart.

01:02:45.500 --> 01:02:49.254
Then one day you find yourself
wondering, "Is this who I really am?

01:02:49.500 --> 01:02:52.731
Someone who has taken up permanent
residence in the valley?

01:02:52.980 --> 01:02:56.575
Or is this just who I am
with this person?"

01:02:57.900 --> 01:03:00.334
And then, you ask yourself:

01:03:00.580 --> 01:03:03.970
"Maybe there is another version
of my life, of myself...

01:03:04.220 --> 01:03:06.336
... that's a happier one."

01:03:22.980 --> 01:03:24.299
Bullshit.

01:03:25.940 --> 01:03:28.977
"Yossel looked into Minnie's eyes
and felt. . .

01:03:30.580 --> 01:03:31.774
. . .nothing.

01:03:32.100 --> 01:03:36.139
For two years they'd been apart.

01:03:36.380 --> 01:03:39.611
And now, as she stepped off the boat. . .

01:03:39.860 --> 01:03:42.772
. . .he realized he was
looking into the eyes. . .

01:03:44.100 --> 01:03:45.613
. . .of a stranger.

01:03:47.580 --> 01:03:49.810
A girl he no longer knew.

01:03:50.420 --> 01:03:53.776
He had become an American.

01:03:54.420 --> 01:03:59.016
And she was still the poor. . .

01:04:02.020 --> 01:04:03.931
. . .unaffectionate. . .

01:04:04.780 --> 01:04:06.133
. . .daughter. . .

01:04:07.860 --> 01:04:11.091
. . .of a blind Lithuanian
violin maker."

01:04:12.420 --> 01:04:16.015
It's fear. It was all about fear.
Fear's what kept them together.

01:04:16.260 --> 01:04:19.457
This whole time I've idealized
my grandparents' marriage.

01:04:19.700 --> 01:04:22.168
But this was not the love of the ages.

01:04:22.420 --> 01:04:25.378
The two stayed together
because they were terrified.

01:04:25.620 --> 01:04:28.657
Fear of loneliness, fear of failure,
fear of the unknown.

01:04:28.900 --> 01:04:32.290
Sure, fear. That's the main
motivator for everything.

01:04:32.540 --> 01:04:35.816
That and guilt are the two emotions
that keep a society humming.

01:04:36.060 --> 01:04:38.255
You and Rachel stay together
because of fear?

01:04:38.500 --> 01:04:40.252
-In a word, yes.
-You're okay with that?

01:04:40.500 --> 01:04:42.616
In three words, yes and no.

01:04:43.100 --> 01:04:46.809
See, it's not that simple.
You're looking for clear-cut answers.

01:04:47.060 --> 01:04:50.336
In reality, there's nothing clear-cut.
Life is not clear-cut.

01:04:50.580 --> 01:04:52.457
Life is gray.

01:04:52.700 --> 01:04:54.019
For instance:

01:04:55.740 --> 01:04:57.492
What do you see right here?

01:04:59.380 --> 01:05:02.497
-What are you asking me?
-I'm asking you, what do you see?

01:05:02.740 --> 01:05:04.219
I see your ass.

01:05:04.620 --> 01:05:08.659
That's what you think you see.
But in reality, there is no ass.

01:05:10.260 --> 01:05:12.979
What the f--?
What are you telling me?

01:05:13.180 --> 01:05:17.731
There is no ass, just the fatty part
at the top of each leg. . .

01:05:17.980 --> 01:05:20.255
. . .that is butted up
against each other.

01:05:20.500 --> 01:05:21.979
Hence the word "butt."

01:05:22.220 --> 01:05:23.858
See, essentially. . .

01:05:24.100 --> 01:05:27.615
. . .what we're dealing with here is
just a continuation of the leg.

01:05:27.860 --> 01:05:29.896
Okay, all right, now you lost me.

01:05:30.740 --> 01:05:34.255
It's all illusions.
There is no such thing as an ass.

01:05:34.500 --> 01:05:38.652
Just like there's no such thing as
the perfect marriage, job or child.

01:05:38.900 --> 01:05:42.939
The whole notion of staying together
and living happily ever after. . .

01:05:43.180 --> 01:05:44.499
. . .all illusions.

01:05:44.740 --> 01:05:47.379
You're saying you don't believe
in everlasting love?

01:05:48.540 --> 01:05:52.055
You're seeing the ass again
and not the tops of the legs.

01:05:53.140 --> 01:05:56.416
Love is just lust in disguise.
And lust fades.

01:05:56.660 --> 01:06:00.050
So you damn well better be
with someone who can stand you.

01:06:00.300 --> 01:06:03.849
Katie and I have moved way past
being able to stand each other.

01:06:04.100 --> 01:06:06.056
We've moved right
into the hatred part.

01:06:06.300 --> 01:06:09.019
I wouldn't worry about it.
Hate fades.

01:06:10.020 --> 01:06:11.578
Hate fades?

01:06:13.780 --> 01:06:17.659
That's what you're gonna send me out
into the world with?

01:06:17.900 --> 01:06:21.449
"Hate fades. Love is lust.
There is no ass."

01:06:22.620 --> 01:06:25.293
What a disappointment
you've turned out to be.

01:06:28.180 --> 01:06:29.852
Just promise me one thing.

01:06:30.100 --> 01:06:33.775
Please promise me that you will not
say any of this to Rachel.

01:06:34.020 --> 01:06:36.614
Are you crazy?
This conversation ends here.

01:06:37.100 --> 01:06:39.660
When Stan called me,
I couldn't believe it.

01:06:39.860 --> 01:06:41.816
I knew it was rough for you guys--

01:06:42.060 --> 01:06:44.938
We didn't wanna say until we knew
we weren't getting back together.

01:06:45.180 --> 01:06:46.659
Oh, my God.

01:06:49.300 --> 01:06:50.289
How are you doing?

01:06:50.540 --> 01:06:53.293
I don't know.
I thought I'd be devastated.

01:06:53.540 --> 01:06:55.815
Maybe it just hasn't hit me.

01:06:58.140 --> 01:07:01.450
-You're having an affair.
-What are you talking about?

01:07:01.700 --> 01:07:04.339
You're only not devastated
if you're seeing someone else.

01:07:04.540 --> 01:07:06.098
I'm not seeing someone else.

01:07:06.300 --> 01:07:08.211
Are you serious about
who you're not seeing?

01:07:08.420 --> 01:07:10.695
I don't know.
I know he's nothing like Ben.

01:07:10.940 --> 01:07:13.773
He's responsible, plans ahead,
has a Swiss Army knife.

01:07:14.020 --> 01:07:15.533
He even wants to cook me dinner.

01:07:15.780 --> 01:07:17.259
-He's a sandbag.
-A what?

01:07:17.500 --> 01:07:19.855
He's just a sandbag
against the storm. . .

01:07:20.100 --> 01:07:22.933
. . .holding off the inevitable
devastation.

01:07:25.580 --> 01:07:27.298
Rachel, you okay?

01:07:29.900 --> 01:07:31.128
Honey?

01:07:33.500 --> 01:07:34.819
I'm sorry.

01:07:36.180 --> 01:07:39.490
I know I'm supposed to be the one
holding your hand. . .

01:07:39.740 --> 01:07:41.617
. . .but I just feel terrible.

01:07:42.220 --> 01:07:45.417
I mean, the thought of you guys
not being together. . . .

01:07:45.660 --> 01:07:46.979
You're our best friends.

01:07:47.700 --> 01:07:51.375
Fourth of Julys and Thanksgivings
and Christmases.

01:07:51.980 --> 01:07:54.540
You guys were our
Fred and Ethel Mertz.

01:07:55.020 --> 01:07:57.739
We thought you guys were
our Fred and Ethel Mertz.

01:07:58.860 --> 01:08:00.179
Really?

01:08:00.420 --> 01:08:04.333
I never thought this was
going to happen to me and Ben.

01:08:04.580 --> 01:08:08.050
I thought we were going to be the ones
to go the distance.

01:08:08.300 --> 01:08:12.896
But I just couldn't seem to get him
to put down that purple crayon.

01:08:13.780 --> 01:08:17.613
But that's Ben.
That's who you fell in love with.

01:08:17.859 --> 01:08:20.613
Katie, you are at 80
who you are at 8.

01:08:20.859 --> 01:08:23.294
People don't change!

01:08:23.740 --> 01:08:26.732
People change over time.
You've got to expect that.

01:08:26.979 --> 01:08:31.734
The only way a relationship works is
if people grow and change together.

01:08:32.939 --> 01:08:34.737
Mr. and Mrs. Cogen, Mr. Jordan.

01:08:35.100 --> 01:08:39.093
Nice to have you tonight. Is Mrs.
Jordan not joining us this evening?

01:08:39.340 --> 01:08:43.049
No, she's not. Stan, I told you
to make the reservation for three!

01:08:43.300 --> 01:08:45.450
-I forgot.
-How could you forget that?

01:08:45.700 --> 01:08:48.134
Say it louder. The guy
in the lot didn't hear you.

01:08:48.380 --> 01:08:49.938
It wasn't that loud.

01:08:56.340 --> 01:08:58.456
Did you see Sunday's 7 down?

01:08:58.660 --> 01:09:00.729
-I missed that one.
-Five-letter word.

01:09:01.100 --> 01:09:03.295
"Wants, requirements."

01:09:03.700 --> 01:09:05.372
Rhymes with weeds.

01:09:05.740 --> 01:09:06.649
"Needs"?

01:09:06.899 --> 01:09:09.538
Exactly.
It was a direct attack on me.

01:09:09.779 --> 01:09:11.577
Come on. You're being silly.

01:09:11.779 --> 01:09:13.930
It was just a clue
in a crossword puzzle.

01:09:14.460 --> 01:09:18.247
I know my wife.
She was specifically attacking me.

01:09:18.500 --> 01:09:19.728
And for what?

01:09:20.020 --> 01:09:21.658
For having needs.

01:09:22.380 --> 01:09:24.416
Like having needs is
some terrible thing.

01:09:24.939 --> 01:09:27.818
Show me one person
that doesn't have needs.

01:09:30.260 --> 01:09:33.252
Try this bread dipped in
the olive oil. It's delicious.

01:09:33.500 --> 01:09:34.979
Stan, give Ben the bread!

01:09:35.220 --> 01:09:36.288
Why must you yell?

01:09:36.540 --> 01:09:37.734
-Who yelled?
-You.

01:09:37.939 --> 01:09:38.770
That's not a yell.

01:09:39.020 --> 01:09:41.295
He hears everything as a yell.

01:09:41.540 --> 01:09:43.689
On anyone's yell-o-meter,
that was a yell.

01:09:43.939 --> 01:09:46.010
Was that a yell?
He didn't hear it as a yell.

01:09:46.260 --> 01:09:48.251
His mom was a yeller.
He still hears her.

01:09:48.500 --> 01:09:50.968
How could I hear her?
You drown her out.

01:09:51.220 --> 01:09:52.130
It's true.

01:09:52.380 --> 01:09:54.655
The last few years,
when Katie opened her mouth. . .

01:09:54.900 --> 01:09:56.618
. . .all I'd hear was her mother.

01:09:57.500 --> 01:09:58.489
Dot.

01:09:59.260 --> 01:10:03.651
It wasn't easy for Katie to be raised
by a woman as complicated as Dot.

01:10:03.900 --> 01:10:05.777
Please, she wasn't complicated.

01:10:06.020 --> 01:10:09.615
She was an idiot who made
everyone else's life complicated.

01:10:09.860 --> 01:10:13.091
You wouldn't believe the beautiful
psychological heirlooms. . .

01:10:13.340 --> 01:10:15.331
. . .this snapping turtle handed down.

01:10:15.740 --> 01:10:18.049
Everything's gotta be
in a neat little box. . .

01:10:18.300 --> 01:10:20.575
. . .with a little blue bow on it.

01:10:20.900 --> 01:10:22.128
Punctual.

01:10:22.380 --> 01:10:23.574
Ordered.

01:10:23.820 --> 01:10:26.812
God forbid anything unexpected
should happen. . .

01:10:27.060 --> 01:10:30.211
. . .any perchances, happenstances. . .

01:10:30.460 --> 01:10:33.179
. . .left turns, serendipities!

01:10:33.420 --> 01:10:35.809
Nope, no way! Not allowed!

01:10:36.060 --> 01:10:38.369
Out-of-bounds! Foul ball!

01:10:38.580 --> 01:10:42.493
1 5-yard penalty!
Too much time being spontaneous!

01:10:42.740 --> 01:10:45.732
Everything's gotta be connected.
Gotta connect the dots.

01:10:45.980 --> 01:10:47.936
Maybe that's why they call her Dot.

01:10:48.180 --> 01:10:51.570
You notice that her name wasn't
Gay or Joy or Fun!

01:10:51.820 --> 01:10:53.014
Try the bread--

01:10:53.260 --> 01:10:55.774
You can't even fuck
unless everything's just right!

01:10:56.340 --> 01:11:00.458
Like a plane waiting for takeoff.
Windows shut? Check.

01:11:00.700 --> 01:11:04.136
Doors locked? Check!
Heat on? Check!

01:11:04.380 --> 01:11:07.053
Have we covered every possible,
single reason. . .

01:11:07.300 --> 01:11:08.858
. . .why everything is my fault?!

01:11:09.140 --> 01:11:13.452
Houston, we got a problem
and her name is Dot!

01:11:13.660 --> 01:11:16.458
-Ben, bread.
-There are people like Katie and Dot. . .

01:11:16.700 --> 01:11:19.214
. . .who color inside the lines,
and people like you. . .

01:11:19.460 --> 01:11:22.577
. . .who wander outside.
That can be a very endearing quality.

01:11:22.820 --> 01:11:25.971
That's why Katie fell in love
with you. Once you have kids--

01:11:26.220 --> 01:11:27.858
I am not a third child!

01:11:28.100 --> 01:11:30.694
Excuse me if my watch
has no hands on it.

01:11:30.940 --> 01:11:34.489
That's fine. It's just, somebody
has to establish the routine--

01:11:34.740 --> 01:11:36.935
Are you saying it's all my fault?!

01:11:37.900 --> 01:11:39.333
It's nobody's fault!

01:11:39.580 --> 01:11:42.572
When people say it's nobody's fault,
they don't mean that.

01:11:42.820 --> 01:11:46.130
They mean it's your fault!
The nobody's fault things are. . .

01:11:46.380 --> 01:11:49.816
. . .hurricanes, earthquakes,
tornadoes, acts of God!

01:11:50.060 --> 01:11:53.769
But when a marriage fails,
it's gotta be somebody's fault!

01:11:53.980 --> 01:11:55.174
And it's not mine!

01:11:56.300 --> 01:11:59.656
Take that fucking bread and shove it
up the tops of your legs!

01:12:41.020 --> 01:12:45.093
Maybe I'm tired! Maybe I'm dealing
with 5000 things all day long!

01:12:45.340 --> 01:12:47.808
Maybe every need you have
doesn 't have to be met...

01:12:48.020 --> 01:12:50.215
...at the exact moment
you need it to be met!

01:12:50.420 --> 01:12:54.015
I'm sick and tired of being
the designated driver of this marriage!

01:12:54.260 --> 01:12:57.013
Nobody designated you!
It's a role you gave yourself!

01:12:57.260 --> 01:13:00.058
Not once have you seen it
through my eyes!

01:13:00.300 --> 01:13:03.610
We don 't have a pea under our mattress.
You know what we have?

01:13:03.820 --> 01:13:06.095
A fucking watermelon!

01:13:15.780 --> 01:13:17.099
You okay?

01:13:18.900 --> 01:13:20.652
Take me to Katie's.

01:13:25.340 --> 01:13:26.898
What are you doing here?

01:13:27.500 --> 01:13:29.809
I wanted to know what
your high was today.

01:13:31.580 --> 01:13:33.571
You should've called.

01:13:34.180 --> 01:13:35.932
My high was about you.

01:13:38.900 --> 01:13:41.619
Tonight I saw myself
through your eyes.

01:13:46.420 --> 01:13:47.648
And I'm sorry.

01:13:48.060 --> 01:13:49.573
It might be a nice touch. . .

01:13:49.780 --> 01:13:52.817
. . .if you add some roasted peanuts
to the sesame--

01:13:58.820 --> 01:14:01.812
At some point we should discuss
how to tell the children.

01:14:32.500 --> 01:14:34.456
How you doing? Come on in.

01:14:35.580 --> 01:14:36.899
This is nice.

01:14:37.140 --> 01:14:38.016
Thanks.

01:14:38.260 --> 01:14:41.138
It's close to the park.
The kids and I can walk.

01:14:41.380 --> 01:14:43.371
You want something to drink?

01:14:43.620 --> 01:14:46.339
I'll take water if you don't have
anything else.

01:14:48.900 --> 01:14:50.811
We have pretty much
anything you want.

01:14:51.060 --> 01:14:52.812
Beer, Gatorade. . .

01:14:53.020 --> 01:14:55.136
. . .fruit juice, iced tea.

01:14:55.380 --> 01:14:56.938
Iced tea is fine.

01:15:04.180 --> 01:15:05.010
Here you go.

01:15:05.660 --> 01:15:07.059
You have a watch.

01:15:09.420 --> 01:15:10.694
Come on in.

01:15:12.700 --> 01:15:14.019
Sit down here.

01:15:23.780 --> 01:15:25.657
I think we should. . . .

01:15:27.500 --> 01:15:31.618
When we pick the kids up Thursday,
we should just tell them that night.

01:15:32.700 --> 01:15:35.533
We don't have to tell them right away.

01:15:35.780 --> 01:15:36.849
Why?

01:15:37.220 --> 01:15:39.575
What will change
between now and Thursday?

01:15:41.700 --> 01:15:43.736
Katie, you're seeing someone else.

01:15:43.980 --> 01:15:46.130
I'm not seeing him.

01:15:46.380 --> 01:15:48.177
We're just talking.

01:15:50.020 --> 01:15:51.009
Right.

01:15:54.420 --> 01:15:57.856
I won't put up with any more of this
bullshit lying to the kids.

01:15:58.100 --> 01:16:01.615
We take them to Chow Fun's, their
favorite restaurant, to tell them.

01:16:01.860 --> 01:16:04.454
We can't really talk at Chow Fun's.

01:16:04.700 --> 01:16:06.975
We'll go to the house
and tell them at dinner.

01:16:07.220 --> 01:16:08.130
After dinner.

01:16:08.380 --> 01:16:10.848
We'll all sit down and. . . .

01:16:11.100 --> 01:16:13.534
Jesus, how do we say this?

01:16:16.780 --> 01:16:20.534
We'll just tell them
how much we love them. . .

01:16:21.380 --> 01:16:23.530
. . .how amazing and beautiful
they are. . .

01:16:23.780 --> 01:16:26.738
. . .so they don't think
that any of this is their fault.

01:16:26.980 --> 01:16:28.857
That's the important thing.

01:16:30.380 --> 01:16:32.052
We'll just say that. . .

01:16:32.580 --> 01:16:34.298
. . .Mommy and Daddy. . .

01:16:35.860 --> 01:16:37.930
. . .or Mom and Dad. . . .

01:16:38.660 --> 01:16:39.888
You think Mom and Dad?

01:16:40.140 --> 01:16:41.289
Mommy and Daddy.

01:16:43.340 --> 01:16:45.979
We'll say that Mommy and Daddy
have grown apart.

01:16:46.540 --> 01:16:50.135
I was just thinking about Erin.
She'll probably say something like:

01:16:50.380 --> 01:16:53.929
"Well, there must be something right
about you guys. . .

01:16:54.180 --> 01:16:58.059
. . .for you to produce
such beautiful and amazing kids."

01:17:01.620 --> 01:17:04.180
She might say something like that,
you know?

01:17:12.780 --> 01:17:15.010
We'll just tell her that they were. . .

01:17:16.380 --> 01:17:18.450
. . .born in love and we'll
always love them. . .

01:17:18.700 --> 01:17:21.294
. . .but Mommy and Daddy
don't love each other anymore.

01:17:23.140 --> 01:17:26.928
Well, wouldn't it be better
if we told them. . .

01:17:29.740 --> 01:17:32.937
. . .we still love each other,
but in a different way?

01:17:34.820 --> 01:17:35.889
Fine.

01:17:37.140 --> 01:17:39.700
-We shouldn't say that?
-I said it was fine.

01:17:40.580 --> 01:17:43.333
Well, it was kind of a weird "fine."

01:17:44.580 --> 01:17:48.812
Should I be thrilled about how we
love each other in a different way?

01:17:59.740 --> 01:18:02.300
-Who is it?
-Mr. Jordan, your couch is here.

01:18:02.500 --> 01:18:05.412
Where have you guys been?
Come on in.

01:18:06.900 --> 01:18:09.619
They were supposed to be here
first thing this morning.

01:18:15.700 --> 01:18:18.260
I'll pick you up at 5:00
on Thursday?

01:18:31.900 --> 01:18:33.219
So is there. . .

01:18:34.380 --> 01:18:36.211
. . .anything else
we need to talk about?

01:18:36.660 --> 01:18:37.649
Like what?

01:18:40.860 --> 01:18:41.849
Nothing.

01:18:44.980 --> 01:18:46.015
Bye.

01:19:06.780 --> 01:19:08.054
What happened to you?

01:19:08.300 --> 01:19:11.212
What happened to that fun girl
with the pith helmet?

01:19:11.420 --> 01:19:15.299
You don 't think I ask myself
that every day?

01:19:15.620 --> 01:19:17.258
I'm talking about a connection!

01:19:17.500 --> 01:19:21.618
A look! Something that says
that we're on the same side here!

01:19:22.580 --> 01:19:25.014
Isn 't this the moment
where one of us says:

01:19:25.260 --> 01:19:27.216
"This is ridiculous.
We love each other.

01:19:27.420 --> 01:19:30.457
All couples go through this.
Let's give it another try"?

01:19:43.020 --> 01:19:44.931
It was supposed to rain today.

01:19:46.340 --> 01:19:47.693
Glad it didn't.

01:19:48.900 --> 01:19:50.049
Me too.

01:19:54.380 --> 01:19:56.450
Turn here. If you take Sepulveda. . . .

01:19:59.060 --> 01:19:59.970
What?

01:20:01.300 --> 01:20:02.415
Nothing.

01:20:15.460 --> 01:20:17.815
Do you, Katie, take Ben...

01:20:18.060 --> 01:20:19.857
. . .to have and to hold. . .

01:20:20.100 --> 01:20:22.136
. . .in sickness and in health. . .

01:20:22.380 --> 01:20:24.211
. . .for better or for worse. . .

01:20:24.620 --> 01:20:27.293
-. . .till death do you part?
-I do.

01:20:30.620 --> 01:20:32.338
It's a boy.
It's a girl.

01:20:32.540 --> 01:20:33.370
It's a bunny!

01:20:33.660 --> 01:20:34.888
It's a home run!

01:20:35.140 --> 01:20:36.334
It's chickenpox.

01:20:36.540 --> 01:20:37.370
It's over.

01:20:37.580 --> 01:20:38.774
I love you.

01:20:39.020 --> 01:20:39.850
Damn you!

01:20:40.060 --> 01:20:40.890
I love you.

01:20:41.780 --> 01:20:42.576
Damn it!

01:20:42.820 --> 01:20:43.696
I love you.

01:20:43.940 --> 01:20:45.532
I love you. I love you. I love you.

01:20:45.780 --> 01:20:47.099
I hate you!

01:20:47.340 --> 01:20:49.092
Fuck me. Fuck me.

01:20:49.340 --> 01:20:50.136
Fuck you!

01:20:53.500 --> 01:20:54.569
I love you.

01:20:54.820 --> 01:20:55.696
I'm pregnant.

01:20:55.940 --> 01:20:57.055
My goldfish died.

01:20:57.300 --> 01:20:58.289
My hamster died.

01:20:58.540 --> 01:20:59.336
My father's dying.

01:20:59.580 --> 01:21:00.729
I'm pregnant.

01:21:20.140 --> 01:21:21.971
Maybe we should separate.

01:21:59.980 --> 01:22:01.891
Mom! Dad!

01:22:02.140 --> 01:22:03.368
You ready?

01:22:07.900 --> 01:22:10.175
What's up? It's good to see you.

01:22:10.420 --> 01:22:11.773
How you doing?

01:22:13.060 --> 01:22:14.049
What's the matter?

01:22:14.500 --> 01:22:16.695
She just missed you, that's all.

01:22:16.940 --> 01:22:19.295
You've both just grown so big.

01:22:19.540 --> 01:22:22.008
Look at you guys.
I hardly recognize you. Wait.

01:22:23.020 --> 01:22:24.089
Which one is Erin?

01:22:24.980 --> 01:22:26.459
Check it out, Dad.

01:22:27.020 --> 01:22:30.649
I guess we know what your high
is today. "Best All-Around Camper."

01:22:30.900 --> 01:22:32.299
Congratulations. Look.

01:22:32.540 --> 01:22:35.691
I guess this calls for a celebration!
Come on! Riverdance!

01:22:36.220 --> 01:22:38.654
I'm the best all-around Riverdancer

01:22:38.900 --> 01:22:42.097
Come on. Kind of like
a little "Latin Lupe Lu" thing.

01:22:42.860 --> 01:22:44.339
Go with the big finish!

01:22:44.820 --> 01:22:46.253
Come on! What?

01:22:46.500 --> 01:22:49.776
-I have to see these kids next summer.
-Come on, we're hungry.

01:22:50.420 --> 01:22:52.411
Okay. All right.

01:22:57.900 --> 01:22:58.855
Let's go home.

01:23:11.220 --> 01:23:13.495
I think we should go to Chow Fun's.

01:23:21.620 --> 01:23:23.053
Chow Fun's?

01:23:25.220 --> 01:23:27.780
We agreed that we
couldn't talk at Chow Fun's.

01:23:28.260 --> 01:23:29.488
I know.

01:23:31.260 --> 01:23:32.329
What are you saying?

01:23:32.740 --> 01:23:34.537
I'm saying Chow Fun's.

01:23:38.700 --> 01:23:41.612
Are you saying Chow Fun's
because you can't face telling them?

01:23:41.860 --> 01:23:44.249
If that's why, don't say Chow Fun's.

01:23:44.500 --> 01:23:48.652
That's not why. I'm saying Chow Fun's
because we're an "us."

01:23:49.900 --> 01:23:52.016
There's a history here. . .

01:23:52.260 --> 01:23:54.933
. . .and histories
don't happen overnight.

01:23:55.700 --> 01:23:57.531
In Mesopotamia or ancient Troy. . .

01:23:57.780 --> 01:24:01.455
. . .or somewhere, there are cities
built on top of other cities. . .

01:24:01.700 --> 01:24:04.772
. . .but I don't wanna build
another city. I like this city.

01:24:05.020 --> 01:24:06.658
I know where we keep the Bactine. . .

01:24:06.900 --> 01:24:10.051
. . .and what mood you're in
by which eyebrow is higher.

01:24:10.300 --> 01:24:14.816
You always know that I'm quiet in
the morning and compensate accordingly.

01:24:15.060 --> 01:24:17.620
That's a dance you perfect over time.

01:24:17.860 --> 01:24:20.613
And it's much harder
than I thought it would be. . .

01:24:20.860 --> 01:24:24.899
. . .but there's more good than bad.
And you don't just give up!

01:24:25.140 --> 01:24:27.608
And it's not for the sake
of the children.

01:24:27.820 --> 01:24:29.856
But they're great kids, aren't they?

01:24:30.100 --> 01:24:32.534
And we made them!
I mean, think about that.

01:24:32.780 --> 01:24:35.738
There were no people there,
and then there were people.

01:24:35.980 --> 01:24:37.299
And then they grew.

01:24:37.980 --> 01:24:41.575
I won't be able to say to some
stranger, "Josh has your hands" . . .

01:24:41.820 --> 01:24:45.256
. . .or "Remember how Erin threw up
at the Lincoln Memorial?"

01:24:45.500 --> 01:24:48.253
And I'll try to relax.

01:24:49.380 --> 01:24:53.055
Let's face it, anybody will have
traits that get on your nerves.

01:24:53.300 --> 01:24:57.054
Why shouldn't it be your annoying
traits? I'm no day at the beach.

01:24:57.300 --> 01:25:00.770
But I do have a good sense
of direction, so I can find the beach.

01:25:00.980 --> 01:25:03.255
Which is not a criticism of yours. . .

01:25:04.420 --> 01:25:06.376
. . .it's just a strength of mine.

01:25:06.580 --> 01:25:11.256
God, you're a good friend.
And good friends are hard to find.

01:25:12.420 --> 01:25:14.650
Charlotte said that
in Charlotte's Web.

01:25:14.900 --> 01:25:16.891
I love the way you read that to Erin.

01:25:17.140 --> 01:25:19.973
You take on the voice of Wilbur
with such commitment. . .

01:25:20.220 --> 01:25:21.858
. . .even when you're bone tired.

01:25:22.100 --> 01:25:25.979
That speaks volumes about character.
And ultimately. . .

01:25:26.460 --> 01:25:29.611
. . .isn't that what it comes down to?
What a person's made of?

01:25:30.060 --> 01:25:33.211
Because that girl
in the pith helmet. . .

01:25:33.460 --> 01:25:35.098
. . .is still in here.

01:25:38.220 --> 01:25:41.257
I didn't even know she existed
until I met you.

01:25:41.500 --> 01:25:43.616
And I'm afraid if you leave. . .

01:25:44.420 --> 01:25:46.217
. . .I may never see her again.

01:25:46.460 --> 01:25:50.055
Even though I said you beat her
out of me. Isn't that the paradox?

01:25:50.300 --> 01:25:53.610
Haven't we hit the essential paradox?
Give and take, push and pull.

01:25:53.860 --> 01:25:56.658
The best of times, the worst of times.
Dickens said it best.

01:25:56.900 --> 01:26:00.575
The Jack Sprat of it. He could eat
no fat. His wife could eat no lean.

01:26:00.820 --> 01:26:04.859
But that doesn't apply here, does it?
I guess what I'm trying to say is. . .

01:26:06.300 --> 01:26:08.609
. . .I'm saying Chow Fun's because. . .

01:26:09.260 --> 01:26:10.773
. . .I love you.

01:26:19.700 --> 01:26:20.928
I love you too.

01:26:28.660 --> 01:26:30.218
Did you hear that, kids?

01:26:30.460 --> 01:26:32.974
Your mom wants to go to Chow Fun's!

01:26:33.980 --> 01:26:36.574
Isn't that great?
I love Chow Fun's!

01:26:36.900 --> 01:26:39.255
The egg rolls are good,
but not that good.

01:26:39.500 --> 01:26:41.377
The egg rolls are fantastic!

01:26:41.580 --> 01:26:43.730
They're warm, crispy,
greasy as all hell.

01:26:43.980 --> 01:26:46.494
-Everything you want in an egg roll!
-Exactly!

01:26:46.740 --> 01:26:48.173
High/Low. Erin, you first.

01:26:48.420 --> 01:26:51.253
My high for the summer is,
Austin wrote me 1 1 1 times.

01:26:51.500 --> 01:26:53.730
How did you come up
with High/Low anyway?

01:26:53.980 --> 01:26:56.448
I don 't know.
But I've got another game.

01:26:56.700 --> 01:26:59.294
I'm thinking of seven words.
What are they?

01:26:59.740 --> 01:27:01.298
Do I get a hint?

01:27:01.620 --> 01:27:02.416
A category?

01:27:02.660 --> 01:27:05.618
-Any seven words in English.
-That's right.

01:27:05.860 --> 01:27:07.009
Fair enough.

01:27:07.980 --> 01:27:10.653
"MacArthur Park is melting
in the dark."

01:27:13.900 --> 01:27:16.812
"And they lived happily ever after."

01:27:17.660 --> 01:27:20.128
That's six words,
but you're very close.

01:27:21.380 --> 01:27:24.497
"And they lived mostly happily
ever after"?

01:27:25.260 --> 01:27:26.659
I hope so.

01:27:27.300 --> 01:27:28.813
I think so.

01:27:30.660 --> 01:27:31.809
Think so?

01:27:32.300 --> 01:27:33.449
I do.

01:27:34.780 --> 01:27:35.974
I do. . .

01:27:36.500 --> 01:27:37.569
. . .too.

